    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a New Yorker and now an intermittent East Hamptonite, I always like to believe I set a trend or at least anticipate one. So I was pleased to see my bus ridership is part of an increasing trend (news article, Dec. 22).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a New Yorker and now an intermittent East Hamptonite, I always like to believe I set a trend or at least anticipate one. So I was pleased to see my bus ridership is part of an increasing trend (news article, Dec. 22).</p>
        <p>As a young boy growing up in northern New Jersey, I used the Port Authority buses to see the big city. Nevertheless, buses in New York seemed unappealing. I never had exact change, and I wasn't sure where I would end up once I got on.</p>
        <p>Now, I find myself almost enjoying Manhattan buses. I have a Metrocard and it works. The crowd is truly a mixed bag of New Yorkers: crying children, elderly folks seeming to be on a leisurely trip and all the ambitious worker bees going to and from the meetings that lead to accomplishments or a vague sense of forward movement.</p>
        <p>STEVEN A. LUDSIN  East Hampton, N.Y., Dec. 22, 1998</p>
      </block>
